# Documentation Standards

## Formatting Guidelines

## Code Comments

Only add comments that explain **why**, not **what**:

```typescript
// Bad: describes what code does (obvious)
// Loop through players and update chips
for (const player of players) {
  player.chips += winnings;
}

// Good: explains non-obvious reasoning
// Process in reverse order to handle side pots correctly
// (largest stacks get remainder from uneven splits)
for (const player of players.reverse()) {
  player.chips += calculateShare(player);
}
```

## JSDoc for Public APIs

Add JSDoc to exported functions/classes used by other modules:

```typescript
/**
 * Evaluates a poker hand and returns its rank.
 * @param cards - Array of 5-7 cards
 * @returns Hand rank and high cards for tiebreaking
 */
export function evaluateHand(cards: Card[]): HandEvaluation {
  // ...
}
```

## README Updates

Keep `README.md` minimal — point to `docs/` for details:

- Quick start instructions
- Link to `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md` for system overview
- Link to `docs/guides/` for specific topics

## Markdown Formatting

- Use ATX headers (`#`, `##`, not underlines)
- Code blocks with language tags
- Tables for structured info
- Keep lines under 100 chars when practical
